# Extending Existing Types

An **Extension** allows you to add brand new Properties and Methods to a Type that *already exists*... even if you didn't write the original code!

For example, we generally can't edit Apple's internal code for `Int`. But using an Extension, we can retroactively inject our own code into it!

```swift
extension Int {
    func squared() -> Int {
        return self * self
    }
}

print(5.squared()) // Prints 25!
```

# Free Default Code

Here is the ultimate secret weapon of Swift architecture.

We know Protocols don't contain actual code, just the rules...
But if we **extend a Protocol**, we CAN provide default code!

```swift
protocol Greeter { func greet() }

// We extend the protocol to do the work!
extension Greeter {
    func greet() {
        print("Hello there!")
    }
}
```
Now, any Struct that adopts `Greeter` gets the `greet()` method completely for free, without writing any code!

